      commentary: `Tamasic giving is characterized by its carelessness: the wrong circumstances, inappropriate recipients, and the two qualities that most reveal the state of the giver — asat-kṛtam (without proper respect, contemptuously handled) and avajñātam (with disdain, looking down on the recipient). The gift is given in a way that diminishes rather than serves.\n\nAdeśa-kāle — wrong place and wrong time. This includes giving in ways that embarrass the recipient, giving what is not needed, giving at moments when the gift creates harm rather than benefit. Wisdom in giving is not about the amount but about the appropriateness. A misapplied gift can be worse than no gift.\n\nAvajñātam — with contempt. This is the most telling quality. The giver who looks down on the recipient, who makes the giving an occasion for the assertion of superiority, who uses the act of charity to reinforce a hierarchy of worth — this is tamasic. The condescension poisons the giving and reveals that the motivation was never really about the other person at all. Genuine sattvic giving flows from a recognition of the shared divine nature of giver and receiver — and from that recognition, contempt is simply impossible.`
