      commentary: `Having analyzed all the forms of tapas and dāna through the three-guṇa lens, the chapter pivots to its ultimate teaching: Om Tat Sat — the three syllables that constitute Brahman's own self-indication. These three are not additions to the threefold framework; they are what makes the framework intelligible. They are the source from which the entire cosmos, including all the sattvic practices just described, emerges.\n\nOm — the primordial sound, the syllable that represents the total of all speech and all meaning. The Mandukya Upaniṣad devotes its entire brief length to Om. It is both the name of Brahman and the form of Brahman in sound. Every mantra, every sacred utterance, every act of genuine communication is ultimately an expression of Om.\n\nTat — That. The absolute pronoun pointing to what cannot be named more specifically. All the descriptions of Brahman in the Gita — the light of lights, neither being nor non-being, the Supreme Person — all of them are attempts to indicate what "Tat" simply points to. Sat — Being, Truth, Existence itself. These three syllables together constitute the fullest possible indication of the ultimate reality. By these, the entire tradition was established; by these, every genuine act of practice is sanctified.`
