      commentary: `The practical application of the Om-Tat-Sat teaching: begin every act of sacrifice, giving, and austerity with Om. Not as a magical incantation but as an orientation — the conscious acknowledgment that this act is being performed in the field of the ultimate reality, in the presence of Brahman, in alignment with what is most real. Om is the opening, the invocation, the surrender.\n\nBrahma-vādinām — for those who speak of Brahman, who are committed to Brahman, whose orientation is toward the ultimate. Not everyone begins their morning in this way. But for those on the path — those who have heard and taken to heart the teaching of the Gita — every significant action begins with this orientation. Not every action is a ritual, but every significant action can be sanctified by this beginning.\n\nVidhānoktāḥ — as prescribed, as ordained. The tradition's prescriptions are not arbitrary. They are the accumulated crystallization of what has been found to work — what genuinely orients consciousness toward the divine. Beginning actions with Om is a small act with significant effect: it shifts the starting orientation of the action from "I am doing this" to "this is arising in the field of Brahman." That shift, sustained through all the practices described in this chapter, is the practical path of Chapter 17.`
