      commentary: `Tat — That — is the syllable of surrender. When action is prefaced with "Tat," the intended orientation is: this is for That, not for me. The seeking of the fruit is suspended. The action is offered into the infinite. Mokṣa-kāṅkṣibhiḥ — seekers of liberation — are those who have seen through the trap of fruit-oriented action and are now performing all their religious and social activities with a different orientation: not for the result but for the offering itself.\n\nAnabhisandhāya phalam — without aiming at the fruit. This is the core of karma-yoga from Chapter 3 reappearing here in a different form. The teaching is consistent throughout the Gita: the action with the fruit released is the liberating action. Hold the fruit, and the action binds. Release it — consciously orient the action toward That, toward the infinite — and the action becomes a vehicle of freedom.\n\nVividhāḥ — various. The diversity of actions is not a problem for this orientation. Whether it is a major sacrifice, a small act of charity, or the discipline of daily practice — all of them can be performed "with Tat," with the consciousness that they are offerings into the infinite rather than transactions with a finite universe. The difference is entirely interior; the actions may look identical from outside.`
