      commentary: `The chapter closes with its most definitive statement, and it reverses all the preceding analysis. All the carefully delineated sattvic practices — the properly performed sacrifice, the correctly motivated giving, the threefold austerity — none of it matters without śraddhā. Without the genuine orientation of the heart, all of it is Asat: non-being, worthless, unreal.\n\nThis is not a contradiction of everything said before. It is its fulfillment. The entire analysis of sattvic vs. rajasic vs. tamasic practice was a preparation for this: the quality that makes any practice genuine is not the external form but the inner śraddhā. And śraddhā, as verse 3 established, is what you fundamentally are. You are your faith. Therefore: every practice is only as real as the faith behind it.\n\nNa ca tat pretya no iha — it is nothing here or hereafter. This is the strongest possible statement of the chapter's teaching. Not "it is less valuable" or "it will not be as effective." Nothing. Worth nothing now, worth nothing after death. The spiritual life, in the Gita's understanding, is not primarily about accumulating the right practices — it is about the quality of orientation behind all practice. Genuine śraddhā in the divine, genuine orientation toward Sat — that is what this entire chapter has been circling. And it is the one thing without which all the rest adds up to Asat.`
